<p>If we overlook these defects the version is one of the best that has appeared so far in English or American hymnals and considerably above the standard of the Moravian hymns of the early eighteenth century. The following lines offer a very true counterpart of the German:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>â€œAll woes give way and flee,â€ line 4</p>

  <p>â€œAnd that in Change and Chances<br />
He stands at my right hand.â€ lines 13, 14</p>

  <p>â€œThe ground of my possession<br />
Is Jesus and his Blood.â€ lines 17, 18</p>

  <p>â€œShould Earth lose its foundation<br />
Thou standâ€™st my lasting Rock.â€ lines 97, 98</p>
</blockquote>

